msgid "Alternate Python source directory (src layout)"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:106
msgid ""
"Having a directory with `package_name` in the root of the project can "
"occasionally cause confusion as Python allows importing local packages and "
"modules. A popular way to avoid this is with the `src`\\-layout, where the "
"Python package is nested within a `src` directory. Unfortunately this "
"interferes with the structure of a typical Rust project. Fortunately, Python "
"is not particular about the name of the parent source directory."
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:113
msgid "maturin will detect the following src layout automatically:"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:128
msgid "Import Rust as a submodule of your project"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:130
msgid ""
"If the Python module created by Rust has the same name as the Python package "
"in a mixed Rust/Python project, IDEs might get confused. You might also want "
"to discourage end users from using the Rust functions directly by giving it "
"a different name, say '\\_my_project'. This can be done by adding `module-"
"name = <package name>.<rust pymodule name>` to the `[tool.maturin]` in your "
"`pyproject.toml`. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:134
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[tool.maturin]\n"
"module-name = \"my_project._my_project\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""
"```toml\n"
"[tool.maturin]\n"
"module-name = \"my_project._my_project\"\n"
"```"

#: src/project_layout.md:139
msgid ""
"You can then import your Rust module inside your Python source as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:145
msgid ""
"IDEs can then recognize the `_my_project` module as separate from your main "
"Python source module. This allows for code completion of the types inside "
"your Rust Python module for certain IDEs."
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:148
msgid "Adding Python type information"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:150
msgid "To distribute typing information, you need to add:"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:152
msgid ""
"an empty marker file called `py.typed` in the root of the Python package"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:153
msgid "inline types in Python files and/or `.pyi` \"stub\" files"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:155
msgid ""
"In a pure Rust project, add type stubs in a `<module_name>.pyi` file in the "
"project root. Maturin will automatically include this file along with the "
"required `py.typed` file for you."
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:168
msgid ""
"In a mixed Rust/Python project, additional files in the Python source dir "
"(but not in `.gitignore`) will be automatically included in the build "
"outputs (source distribution and/or wheel). Type information can be "
"therefore added to the root Python package directory as you might do in a "
"pure Python package. This requires you to add the `py.typed` marker file "
"yourself."
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:190
msgid "Data"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:192
msgid ""
"You can add wheel data by creating a `<module_name>.data` folder or setting "
"its location as `data` in pyproject.toml under `[tool.maturin]` or in Cargo."
"toml under `[project.metadata.maturin]`."
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:194
msgid "The data folder may have the following subfolder:"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:196
msgid ""
"`data`: The contents of this folder will simply be unpacked into the "
"virtualenv"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:197
msgid ""
"`scripts`: Treated similar to entry points, files in there are installed as "
"standalone executable"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:198
msgid "`headers`: For `.h` C header files"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:199
msgid "`purelib`: This also exists, but seems to be barely used"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:200
msgid "`platlib`: This also exists, but seems to be barely used"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:202
msgid ""
"If you add a symlink in the data directory, we'll include the actual file so "
"you have more flexibility."
msgstr ""

